<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,1940,2039]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,153,323]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1940,1967]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1856" box="[555,672,1941,1967]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[555,672,1941,1967]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Megaselia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males of the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[982,1129,1941,1967]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref21228" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplets 47 and 48, but none of the options fit. A dozen omitted or subsequently described species run to these couplets, differences in the hypopygia, costal indexes and/or the colour of the legs and/or palps exclude all but 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz. However" authorityName="Schmitz. However" authorityYear="1948" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="globicornis">
<emphasis box="[1165,1330,2013,2039]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">M. globicornis</emphasis>
Schmitz. However
</taxonomicName>
, the latter has the hairs below the basal half of the hind femur clearly shorter than those of the anteroventral row (
<figureCitation box="[211,308,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 136–139" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1580,1605]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1546]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1435,705,1555]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 136–139. Megaselia globicornis Schmitz, male. 136, left face of hypopygium; 137, left hypandrial lobe; 138, left face of penis complex; 139, hind femur. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573404/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 139</figureCitation>
) and the similar hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[659,817,189,216]" captionStart="FIGURES 136–139" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1580,1605]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1546]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1435,705,1555]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 136–139. Megaselia globicornis Schmitz, male. 136, left face of hypopygium; 137, left hypandrial lobe; 138, left face of penis complex; 139, hind femur. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573404/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs 136–138</figureCitation>
) differs in detail, such its possession of a long, fingerlike, left hypandrial lobe (
<figureCitation box="[450,551,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURES 136–139" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1580,1605]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,705,1546]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1435,705,1555]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 136–139. Megaselia globicornis Schmitz, male. 136, left face of hypopygium; 137, left hypandrial lobe; 138, left face of penis complex; 139, hind femur. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573404/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 137</figureCitation>
). In Schnitz’s (1957) key to the Palaearctic Abteilung II it runs to couplet 20 where the hypopygia of both options are clearly different. It fails to run down for the rest of the world.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
